So much stupid stuff to learn and figure out. :< apparently entity:AddNewModifier(entity, nil, 'my_modifier', { works = 'this part', stuff = { fails = 'hard' } }) the strings get passed to the OnCreated, but tables don't.
So the hackaround is to set the table on the entity, then the modifier can GetParent().stuff table...
Or create the function on the entity, and call back.
Jake | Arhowk 17-Feb-17 02:44 PM
The issue is server/client side networking
AddNewModifier is one of the few server side functions that can natively access client side lua
so when you do stuff like that ur functions wont be visible client side
which is where the "no tables" limitation comes from

israeli cowboys 22-Feb-17 04:35 PM
well in your npc_abilities.txt, a lua ability is basically the same as a datadriven ability except it's ability_lua instead of ability_datadriven as a BaseClass, and you also need to include a ScriptFile keyvalue with the filepath of the .lua file it uses
you can fill its entry in npc_abilities.txt with as much or as little as you want, so long as anything your ability needs that isn't in npc_abilities.txt as a keyvalue is defined in your .lua file

israeli cowboys 22-Feb-17 05:43 PM

https://github.com/Pizzalol/SpellLibrary
quite incomplete but holds a lot of recreations of existing abilities
Sarynth 22-Feb-17 05:45 PM
Abilities are hard coded, so that link is an attempt to recreate the abilities using what we have available.
Also, you can modify existing spells to modify only attributes existing on it, but you can't add things to it.
For example, in /npc/npc_abilities_override.txt you can put lich_frost_nova and set the AbilityManaCost to "25" to override the default one, but you couldn't add in a modifier or something like that. You can't add, just change existing properties.
Otherwise, you'll need to create a custom ability and base it on the spell library. Or create your own.
